resources.string: I have read and I accept these conditions

AtrapaelTigre is now Mosquito Alert!

We are the same team but the project has grown to incorporate a new character: Now you can send reports of not only tiger mosquitoes (Aedes albopictus) but also yellow fever mosquitoes (Aedes aegypti).

You can find more information at www.mosquitoalert.com

Thanks for your interest and participation,

The Mosquito Alert Team

string-array.item: The main difference between the yellow fever mosquito, Ae. aegypti (left), and the tiger mosquito. Ae. albopictus (right), is in the thorax: The yellow fever mosquito has a lyre-shaped mark, while the tiger mosquito has a single white stripe.\u0020\u0020Foto: Vincent Robert (CC BY 2.0)
Tiger mosquito (Aedes albopictus). Its main characteristic is its black body with white spots and a white stripe on the head and thorax. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)

Yellow fever mosquito (Aedes aegypti). Recognized by its dark brown color with white spots and the lyre-shaped mark on its torso. Observe the previous image and compare the colors. Photo: James Gathany (ECDC, domini públic)
Observe the black color that characterizes Ae. albopictus. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)
Observe the brown color of Ae. aegypti. Foto: Mark Yokoyama (CC BY 2.0)
Who bites? Only female mosquitoes, and in this case Ae. albopictus. Urban Aedes usually bite during the day (not at night), and they usually bite legs. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)
Difference between male (left) and female (right) Ae. albopictus. The males have plumes on their heads. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)\n
Aedes eggs. The eggs are so small they are almost invisible to the naked eye. Urban Aedes lay eggs on the dry walls of small vessels near stagnant water. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)

Aedes larvae (longer) and pupae (rounder). Notice that they are aquatic. The larvae emerge from the eggs when the eggs are covered with water, and they eventually turn into pupae. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)
Aedes larvae (longer) and pupae (rounder) in the water. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)

Metamorphosis: Adult mosquito (Ae. albopictus) emerges from pupae into the air. To avoid urban Aedes around your home, remove standing water and flip containers that might accumulate water when it rains or when you water the garden. Photo: Roger Eritja (©)

The tiger mosquito (Ae. albopictus) has a white stripe on its head and thorax. Conversely, the yellow fever mosquito (Ae. aegypti) has several white stripes in its thorax, forming a lyre-shaped pattern. Try not to send reports of mosquitoes that do not have these characteristics.

\n\n

Illustrations: J.Luis Ordóñez, CREAF (CC-BY-NC 3.0). Right photo: James Gathany (ECDC, public domain)

Urban Aedes have white spots on the abdomen and legs, but the white pattern and the body background color are slightly different. Try not to send reports of mosquitoes that do not have these characteristics.

\n\n

Illustrations: J.Luis Ordóñez, CREAF (CC-BY-NC 3.0)
What does your mosquito look like? Check the (i) button and select an answer:

The tiger mosquito (Ae. albopictus) and the yellow fever mosquito (Ae. aegypti) are small and dark with white spots. The body of Ae. albopictus is black, while that of Ae. aegypti is dark brown. Try not to send reports on mosquitoes that do not have these characteristics.

\n

Illustrations: J.Luis Ordóñez, CREAF (CC-BY-NC 3.0)

HELP:

Urban Aedes (the tiger mosquito, Ae. albopictus, and the yellow fever mosquito, Ae. aegypti) are small (less than a cent euro coin) and dark (black or dark brown) with white stripes or spots on their bodies. They are usually aggressive, biting during the day and mostly biting people's legs. They fly low to the ground and are found near houses, in gardens, and in the streets.

If you have found one, fill out this report and send in your data. Fields marked with an asterisk (*) are required.

  • Description: the survey will help you decide if what you've found is Ae. albopictus or Ae. aegypti.

  • Location: Choose current location if you are still in the place where you found the mosquito. (Make sure you have GPS enabled on your phone.) Otherwise, select the mosquito's location on the map.

  • Photo(s): Take a photo of the mosquito now or attach one that you have already taken. The most important thing is to photograph the thorax, making it possible to recognize the white stripe, in the case of Ae. albopictus, or the lyre-shaped mark, in the case of Ae. aegypti. To do this, grab the legs and focus well. If necessary, move the camera a little bit away from the mosquito. You can attach more than one photo, and it is useful if you can capture images from different angles. You will find more tricks in the project website.

  • Notes: Add a note if you want to send additional information about your finding. Don’t include personal information.

Once sent, you can view and edit your report on your phone by selecting the map activity from the main screen and then clicking on a report icon. The information you submit will also be published on a public webmap at www.mosquitoalert.com .

HELP:

Urban Aedes (Ae. albopictus and Ae. aegypti) breed in small containers (even smaller than a bucket), usually in the outside with stagnant water inside. Water should be present for a few days so that larvae and pupae can develop and do the metamorphosis to adult mosquitoes. If you have found a breeding site, especially a storm drain in a public area, fill out this report and send in your data. Fields marked with an asterisk (*) are required.

  • Description: answer the survey.

  • Location: Choose current location if you are still at the site. (Make sure you have GPS enabled on your phone.) Otherwise, select the site's location on the map.

  • Photo(s): Take a photo of the site now or attach one from a file. If you can, take a picture in which the site can be recognized, and another showing the stagnant water and/or larvae or pupae.

  • Notes: Add a note if you want to send additional information about your finding. Don’t add personal information.

Once sent, you can view and edit your report on your phone by selecting the map activity from the main screen and then clicking on a report icon. The information you submit will also be published on a public webmap at www.mosquitoalert.com .

Urban Aedes (Ae. albopictus and Ae. aegypti) generally lay eggs in small containers (even smaller than a bucket) containing stagnant water, usually outdoors. Storm drains that accumulate water can be important breeding sites for these species.

\n

Urban Aedes\u0020\u0020do not breed on beaches or in rivers, lakes, ponds, or wetlands.

\u0020\u0020\u0020\u0020\u0020\u0020\u0020\n

A number of these images have been donated by the Barcelona Public Health Agency.
Public areas are those with free access to the public, like roads, squares, parks, and green spaces. They do not include private lots and or other private properties.
In order to survive, the larvae and pupae of urban Aedes need stagnant and turbid water available for several days before they metamorphosise into adult mosquitoes.
The tiger mosquito does not normally travel far, so adults are often found near their breeding sites.\n\n\u0020\u0020\u0020\u0020
